1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,000
 Welcome to C Programming for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance and this is my reading of the 1978 C Programming book written by Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie. At times I add my own interpretation of the material from a historical perspective.

2
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 Chapter 6, Structures. A structure is a collection of one or more variables, possibly of different types, grouped together under a single name for convenient handling.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 While we talk about data structures and how to use them in every language, this section is about understanding how software developers carefully control the low level shape of their data items to solve their problems.

4
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:57,000
 When you first learn about the C struct keyword, you might think it's equivalent to a Python dict. A dynamic key value store like a PHP array, Java, MyApp, or JavaScript object, but nothing is further from the truth. These other languages provide us with easy to use data structures where all of the challenging problems are solved.

5
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:12,000
 This chapter tells, or told, the creators of Python, PHP, Java, and JavaScript how to solve the complex problems and build convenient and flexible data structures which we now all use in those object oriented languages.

6
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:36,000
 One way to look at this code in the chapter is to think of it as a lesson on how one might build Python's list and dict data structures. If the code in the chapter takes you a little while to figure out, mentally make a note of thanks for all the hard work that modern languages invest to make their high level data structures flexible and easy to use.

7
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 Back to the textbook. Their traditional example of a structure is a payroll record. An employee is described as a set of attributes such as name, address, social security number, salary, etc.

8
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 Some of these in turn could be structures, a name has several components as does an address and even a salary. Structures help organize complicated data, particularly in large programs, because in many situations they permit a group of related variables to be treated as a unit instead of separate entities.

9
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 In this chapter, we'll try to illustrate how structures are used. The programs that we will use are bigger than many others in the book, but are still of modest size.

10
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:28,000
 Section 6.1 basics. Let us revisit the date conversion routines of Chapter 5. A date consists of several parts such as the day, month, and year, and perhaps the day of the year and the month name.

11
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 These five variables can all be placed in a single structure like this. Struct, date, open curly brace, int day semicolon, int month semicolon, int year semicolon, int year day semicolon, char, mon name, open square bracket for, close square bracket semicolon, curly brace, semicolon.

12
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 The keyword struct introduces a structure declaration, which is a list of declarations in closed embraces. An optional name called the structure tag may follow the word struct as with date here.

13
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 The tag names this kind of a structure and can subsequently be used as shorthand for the detailed declaration. The elements or variables mentioned in a structure are called its members. A structure, member, or tag and ordinary, i.e. non-member variable, can have the same name without conflict, since they are always distinguished by context.

14
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 Of course, as a matter of style, one would normally use the same names only for closely related objects.

15
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 The right brace that terminates the list of members may be followed by a list of variables, just as for any basic type.

16
00:03:40,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 That is, struct, open curly brace, dot dot dot, close curly brace, x comma y comma z semicolon, is syntactically analogous to int, x comma y comma z semicolon, in the sense that each statement declares x, y, and z to be variables of the named type and causes space to be allocated for them.

17
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 A structured declaration that is not followed by a list of variables allocates no storage. It merely describes a template or the shape of the structure.

18
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 If the declaration is tagged, however, the tag can be used in later definitions of the actual instances of the structure.

19
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 For example, given the declaration of date above, struct, date, d defines a variable d which is a structure of type date. An external or static structure can be initialized by following its definition with a list of initializers for the components.

20
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 Struct, date, d equals open curly brace, 14 comma 7 comma 1776 comma 186 comma double quote jul double quote close curly brace semicolon.

21
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 A member of a particular structure is referred to in an expression by construction of the form structure name dot member.

22
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:24,000
 The structure member operator dot connects the structure name and the member name. To set leap from the date in structure d, for example, leap equals d dot year modulo 4 double equals 0 and d dot year modulo 100 not equal to 0 or d dot year modulo 400 double equals 0 semicolon.

23
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 Or to check the month name, if open paren strcmp open paren d dot mun name comma double quote auj double quote close paren double equals 0 close paren dot dot dot.

24
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:53,000
 Or to convert the first character of the month name to lowercase, d dot mun name sub 0 equals lower open paren d dot mun name sub 0 close paren semicolon.

25
00:05:53,000 --> 00:06:12,000
 Structures may be nested. A payroll record might actually look like struct person open curly brace char name open square bracket name size close square bracket semicolon, char address open square bracket adder size close square bracket semicolon, long zip code semicolon,

26
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 long ss number semicolon, double salary, struct date birthdate semicolon, struct date higher date semicolon, close curly brace semicolon.

27
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 The person structure contains two dates. If we declare emp as struct person emp semicolon, then emp dot birthdate dot month refers to the month of birth.

28
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 The structure member operator dot associates left to right.

29
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 Section 6.2 Structures and Functions.

30
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 There are a number of restrictions on C structures. The essential rules are that only operations you can perform on a structure are to take its address with ampersand and access one of its members.

31
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 This implies that structures may not be assigned or copied to as a unit and that they cannot be passed or returned from functions.

32
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 These restrictions will be removed in forthcoming versions.

33
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 Bonus to structures do not suffer these limitations, however, so structures and functions do work together comfortably.

34
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:22,000
 Finally, automatic structures like automatic arrays cannot be initialized.

35
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 Only external or static structures can.

36
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 This prediction was indeed accurate. Modern C compilers do support the copying of a structure with a single assignment statement.

37
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:37,000
 Given that a C structure is just a fixed length block of memory, it's easy to generate machine code to copy it.

38
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 A key bit to remember that when the C structure is copied, it is done as a shallow copy.

39
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,000
 A shallow copy copies the values of the variables and the pointers in the structure, but does not make copies of any data which the pointers point to.

40
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 A structure that contains other structures, i.e. not pointers to structures, then those structures are shallow copied as well.

41
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
 Back to the text.

42
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 Let us investigate some of these points by rewriting the date conversion functions in the last chapter to use structures.

43
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 Since the rules prohibit passing of a structure to a function directly, we must either pass the components separately or pass a pointer to the whole thing.

44
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 The first alternative uses of day of year, which as we wrote in chapter 5. D.YearDay = DayOfYear(D.Year,D.Month,D.Day,Semicolon)

45
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 The other way is to pass a pointer.

46
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 If we have declared higherDate as struct Date higherDate Semicolon and rewritten DayOfYear, we could then say higherDate.YearDay = DayOfYear(&higherDate,Semicolon)

47
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:57,000
 to pass a pointer to higherDate to DayOfYear. The function has to be modified because its argument is now a pointer rather than a list of variables.

48
