244
00:53:35,040 --> 00:53:48,040
 Before we leave this example, it's also worth a brief digression on a problem related to storage allocators. Clearly, it's desirable that there only be one storage allocator in a program, even though it allocates different kinds of objects.

245
00:53:48,040 --> 00:53:56,040
 But if one allocator is to process requests for, say, pointers to chars and pointers to struct T nodes, two questions arise.

246
00:53:56,040 --> 00:54:08,040
 First, does it meet the requirement of most real machines that objects of a certain types must satisfy alignment restrictions? For example, integers must often be located on even addresses.

247
00:54:08,040 --> 00:54:27,040
 Second, what declarations can cope with the fact that alloc necessarily returns different kinds of pointers? Alignment requirements can generally be satisfied easily at the cost of some wasted space merely by ensuring the allocator always returns a pointer that meets all alignment restrictions.

248
00:54:27,040 --> 00:54:41,040
 For an example, in the PDP-11, it is sufficient that alloc always returns an even pointer since any type of object may be stored at an even address. The only cost is a wasted character on the odd length requests.

249
00:54:41,040 --> 00:54:58,040
 Similar actions are taken on other machines. Thus, the implementation of alloc may not be portable, but its usage is. The alloc of Chapter 5 does not guarantee any particular alignment. In Chapter 8, we'll show how to do the job right.

250
00:54:58,040 --> 00:55:18,040
 As an aside, by now you know that when the authors mention the PDP-11, they are sharing some aspects of the challenge of making C work on previous generation computers with short memory words and small amounts of memory, and at the same time making them work well on the incoming generation of computers with larger words and more memory.

251
00:55:18,040 --> 00:55:31,040
 The research thought and care that went into making sure the C code was portable across multiple generations of computer hardware is on display in the previous paragraph.

252
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:48,040
 The question of the type declaration for alloc is a vexing one for any language that takes its type checking seriously. In C, the best procedure is to declare that alloc returns a pointer to char, and then explicitly coerce the pointer into the desired type with a cast.

253
00:55:48,040 --> 00:56:10,040
 Therefore, if p is declared as char * p; then openparen struct tnode * closeparen p converts it into a tnode pointer expression. Thus, t-alloc is written as struct tnode * t-alloc openparen closeparen open-kirley-brace char * alloc

254
00:56:10,040 --> 00:56:22,040
 return openparen openparen struct tnode * closeparen alloc openparen sizeof openparen struct tnode closeparen closeparen closeparen

255
00:56:22,040 --> 00:56:30,040
 This is more than is needed for current compilers, but represents the safest course for the future.

256
00:56:30,040 --> 00:56:41,040
 I would add that these concerns that the authors mention in this section are also nicely resolved in modern C compilers. In the NC version of C, they introduced the notion of the void type.

257
00:56:41,040 --> 00:56:51,040
 The void type indicates the lack of a type, much like null is used to indicate not a valid pointer or not a flying toy.

258
00:56:51,040 --> 00:57:02,040
 In 1978, because the char type was generally the most native type on any system, it was often used as the generic pointer needed to return memory from an allocation function.

259
00:57:02,040 --> 00:57:10,040
 In modern C, we use pointers to void and then cast the returning pointer to be a pointer to whatever struct or other data we just allocated.

260
00:57:10,040 --> 00:57:17,040
 If we were writing alloc, the alloc routine in this book using modern C, it would return a pointer to void.

261
00:57:17,040 --> 00:57:28,040
 The 1978 version is char * alloc openparen closeparen and the modern version is void * alloc openparen closeparen.

262
00:57:28,040 --> 00:57:47,040
 We've left the book alone, we haven't used void throughout the book, but it is a testament to the foresight of the authors that all the pointer casting code in this book still works today the same, regardless of whether the memory allocation functions return char or void pointers to the allocated data.

