 A singly linked list is also part of a hash map implementation, so you can compare it to the doubly linked list code introduced in the earlier bonus section 6.5.1.

266
00:58:16,040 --> 00:58:33,040
 This section is worth understanding well because not only is it an excellent review of pointers and structures, but also because one of the most common questions on a face-to-face programming interview is draw a hash map on the whiteboard and explain how it works.

267
00:58:33,040 --> 00:58:41,040
 This is an easy question if you study and understand this section of the book, and almost impossible if you have not.

268
00:58:41,040 --> 00:58:46,040
 In some ways, this section is the most intricate data structure that's described in the book.

269
00:58:46,040 --> 00:58:49,040
 It is why it is so popular in coding interviews.

270
00:58:49,040 --> 00:58:55,040
 Chapters 7 and 8 talk about lots of practical things like input/output of the UNIX operating system.

271
00:58:55,040 --> 00:59:00,040
 Elegant data structures and their use are core concepts in computer science.

272
00:59:00,040 --> 00:59:06,040
 Understanding them highlights the difference between a good programmer and a computer scientist.

273
00:59:06,040 --> 00:59:12,040
 In a sense, understanding how a hash map is the secret handshake of computer science.

274
00:59:12,040 --> 00:59:29,040
 And it is the secret handshake because of this book and this section of this book written back in 1978 and used in a course that the person interviewing you may have took when they were in college.

275
00:59:29,040 --> 00:59:37,040
 Hash maps were difficult for them to understand back then, and so if you understand the concept, then you must be solid.

276
00:59:37,040 --> 00:59:43,040
 So I hope you pay close attention to this section and remember the handshake.

277
00:59:43,040 --> 00:59:46,040
