278
00:59:46,040 --> 00:59:53,040
 In this section, we will write the innards of a table lookup package as an illustration of more aspects of structures.

279
00:59:53,040 --> 01:00:00,040
 This code is typical of what might be found in the symbol table management routines of a macro processor or a compiler.

280
01:00:00,040 --> 01:00:03,040
 For example, consider the C pound-to-find statement.

281
01:00:03,040 --> 01:00:13,040
 When a line like pound-to-find yes one is encountered, the name replacement text, the name yes and the replacement text one are stored in a table.

282
01:00:13,040 --> 01:00:20,040
 Later, when the name yes appears in a statement like inward equals yes semicolon, it must be replaced by one.

283
01:00:20,040 --> 01:00:25,040
 There are two major routines that manipulate the names and replacement text.

284
01:00:25,040 --> 01:00:32,040
 Install open paren s comma t closed paren records the name s and replacement t in the table.

285
01:00:32,040 --> 01:00:35,040
 S and t are just character strings.

286
01:00:35,040 --> 01:00:44,040
 Lookup open paren s closed paren searches for s in the table and returns a pointer to the place where it was found or null if it wasn't there.

287
01:00:44,040 --> 01:00:47,040
 The algorithm used is a hash search.

288
01:00:47,040 --> 01:00:55,040
 The incoming name is converted to a small positive integer, which is then used to index into an array of pointers.

289
01:00:55,040 --> 01:01:01,040
 An array element points to the beginning of a chain of blocks describing the names that have the hash value.

290
01:01:01,040 --> 01:01:06,040
 And if it is null, then no names have hashed to that value.

291
01:01:06,040 --> 01:01:15,040
 A block in the chain is a structure containing pointers to the name, the replacement text, and the next block in the chain.

292
01:01:15,040 --> 01:01:20,040
 A null next pointer marks the end of the chain.

293
01:01:20,040 --> 01:01:36,040
 Struct enlist open paren char star name semicolon char star def semicolon struct enlist star next semicolon closed curly brace semicolon.

294
01:01:36,040 --> 01:01:51,040
 The pointer array is just pound define hash size 100 static struct enlist star hash tab open square bracket hash size closed square bracket semicolon.

295
01:01:51,040 --> 01:02:02,040
 The hashing function, which is used by both lookup and install, simply adds up the character values in the string and forms the remainder module of the array size.

296
01:02:02,040 --> 01:02:09,040
 This is not the best possible algorithm, but it has the merit of extreme simplicity.

297
01:02:09,040 --> 01:02:32,040
 Hash open paren s close paren char star s semicolon open curly brace int hash val for open curly brace hash val equals zero star s not equal quote single quote backslash zero single quote semicolon close paren.

298
01:02:32,040 --> 01:02:47,040
