01:10:08,040 --> 01:10:17,040
 even with virtual memory programmers must carefully manage their use of dynamically allocated memory because memory is never unlimited

350
01:10:17,040 --> 01:10:33,040
 section 6.7 fields when stored spaces at a premium it may be necessary to pack several objects into a single machine word one especially common use is a set of single bit at flags and applications like compiler symbol tables

351
01:10:33,040 --> 01:10:42,040
 externally imposed data formats such as interfaces to hardware devices also often require the ability to get at pieces of a word

352
01:10:42,040 --> 01:11:03,040
 as an aside we are going to go now from low level programming to even lower level programming the unix operating system is written in C and unix needs to have for example an implementation of the internet protocol so it can be connected to the internet one of the most important internet protocols is the transmission control protocol TCP

353
01:11:03,040 --> 01:11:24,040
 in order to implement TCP you need to send very precisely formatted data across the network the data is very tightly packed in order to save precious network bandwidth the exact format of a TCP header is described in the TCP Wikipedia page if you look at the header you will find that it bits 96 through 99

354
01:11:24,040 --> 01:11:41,040
 TCP expects a four bit integer that defines the data offset exactly what this data means is less relevant unless you're actually writing the TCP implementation but it does demonstrate that we need to control our data layout at times on a bit by bit basis

355
01:11:41,040 --> 01:12:00,040
 this section covers how we can use struct to build up a TCP header in C, which can be parsed and set without using masking and shifting operations with hard coded numbers. The section below is simpler than constructing a valid TCP header using a carefully packed struct, but it does lay the groundwork for these more complex situations.

356
01:12:00,040 --> 01:12:16,040
 Now back to the text. Imagine a fragment of a compiler that manipulates a symbol table. Each identifier in a program has certain information associated with it for example, whether or not it's a keyword, whether or not it's external and or static and so on.

357
01:12:16,040 --> 01:12:37,040
 The most compact way to encode such information is a set of one bit flags in a single char or int. The usual way this is done is define a set of masks corresponding to the relevant bit positions as in pound define keyword 01, pound define external 02, and pound define static 04.

358
01:12:37,040 --> 01:12:50,040
 The numbers of course must be powers of 2 so that the shifting works. Then accessing the bits become a matter of bit fiddling with shifting, masking, and complementing operators which were described in Chapter 2.

359
01:12:50,040 --> 01:13:09,040
 Certain idioms appear frequently flags vertical par equals external vertical bar static turns on the external and static bits and flags while flags ampersand equal tilde open paren external or static close paren semicolon turns them off.

360
01:13:09,040 --> 01:13:23,040
 And if open paren open paren flags ampersand paren external vertical bar static close paren close paren equal equal zero dot dot dot is true if both bits are off.

361
01:13:23,040 --> 01:13:39,040
 Although these idioms are readily mastered as an alternative see offers the capability of defining and accessing fields within a word directly, rather than by bitwise logical operators. A field is a set of adjacent bits within a single int.

362
01:13:39,040 --> 01:13:57,040
 The syntax of field definition and access is based on structures. For example, the symbol table pound defines above could be replaced by the definition of three fields struct unsigned is keyword colon one semicolon unsigned is

363
01:13:57,040 --> 01:14:11,040
 external colon one semicolon unsigned is static colon one semicolon close curly brace flags. This defines a variable called flags that contains three one bit fields.

364
01:14:11,040 --> 01:14:28,040
 The number following the colon represents the field with in bits. The fields are declared unsigned to emphasize that they are really unsigned quantities individual fields are referenced as flags is keyword flags is external, etc.

365
01:14:28,040 --> 01:14:37,040
 Just like other structure members fields behave like small unsigned integers and may participate in arithmetic expressions just like the other integers.

366
01:14:37,040 --> 01:14:52,040
 Thus the previous examples may be written much more naturally as flags is underscore extern equals flags is static equals one semicolon turn the bits on.

367
01:14:52,040 --> 01:15:16,040
 Flags is external equals flags is static equals one semicolon to turn the bits on flags is external equals flags is static equals zero turns them off. And if open print flags is external double equals zero and flags is static double equals zero close print dot dot dot to test them.

368
01:15:16,040 --> 01:15:29,040
 A field may not overlap an int boundary. If the width would cause this to happen the field is aligned to the next int boundary fields need not be named unnamed fields with a colon and width only are used for padding.

369
01:15:29,040 --> 01:15:45,040
 Special with zero may be used to force alignment to the next int boundary. There are a number of caveats that apply to fields perhaps the most significant fields are assigned left to right on some machines and right to left on others reflecting the nature of different hardware.

370
01:15:45,040 --> 01:15:59,040
 This means that although fields are quite useful for maintaining internally defined data structures, the question of which end comes first has to has to be carefully considered when picking apart externally defined data.

371
01:15:59,040 --> 01:16:12,040
 Other restrictions to bear in mind fields are unsigned, they may only be stored in ints or equivalently unsigned. They are not arrays and they do not have addresses, so the ampersand operator cannot be applied to them.

372
01:16:12,040 --> 01:16:22,040
 Section 6.8 unions. A union is a variable which may hold at different times objects of different types and sizes.

373
01:16:22,040 --> 01:16:35,040
 With a compiler keeping track of the size and alignment requirements, unions provide a way to manipulate different kinds of data in a single area of storage without embedding any machine dependent information in the program.

374
01:16:35,040 --> 01:16:47,040
 For example, again from a compiler symbol table, suppose constants may be ints, floats or character pointers. The value of a particular constant must be stored in a variable of the proper type.

375
01:16:47,040 --> 01:16:56,040
 Yet it is most convenient for table management if the value occupies the same amount of storage and is stored in the same place regardless of its type.

376
01:16:56,040 --> 01:17:04,040
 This is the purpose of a union to provide a single variable which can legitimately hold one of several types.

377
01:17:04,040 --> 01:17:21,040
 As with fields, the syntax is based on structures. Union, utag, open curly brace, int, ival, float, fval, char, star, pval, close curly brace, uval.

378
01:17:21,040 --> 01:17:29,040
 The variable uval will be large enough to hold the largest of these three types regardless of the machine it is compiled on.

379
01:17:29,040 --> 01:17:39,040
 The code is independent of hardware characteristics. Any one of these types may be assigned to uval and then used in expressions so long as the usage is consistent.

380
01:17:39,040 --> 01:17:47,040
 The type retrieved must be the type most recently stored. It is the responsibility of the programmer to keep track of what type is currently stored in a union.

381
01:17:47,040 --> 01:17:55,040
 The results are machine dependent if something is stored as one type and extracted as another type.

382
01:17:55,040 --> 01:18:06,040
 Syntactically, members of a union are accessed as union name dot member or union pointer right arrow member, justice for structures.

383
01:18:06,040 --> 01:18:13,040
 If the variable utype is used to keep track of the current type stored in uval, then one might see code as

384
